Key Insights & Analysis

  • Health Impact: Average of 7.8 estimated respiratory cases per day
  • Pollution Levels: PM2.5 average of 82.6 µg/m³ (exceeds WHO guidelines)
  • Primary Correlate: PM10 (ug/m3) shows strongest correlation (r = 0.280)
  • Data Quality: 100.0% complete

Key Characteristics

  • Respiratory disease epicenter (32% of all diseases). Severe healthcare infrastructure collapse (20% access)
  • Pediatric health emergency (33% children affected). Environmental health disaster (air pollution + healthcare gaps)
  • Patna demonstrates the most severe combination of high disease burden + healthcare infrastructure failure among all cities
    •

    *Synthetic Data Considerations

  • Population: ~2.69M (metro 2025); literacy 83.37%; sex ratio 894/1000; predominantly Hindu
  • Respiratory Disease: Very high burden—ARI cases 1.28M statewide (2018); Patna had 20,083 ARI cases; 32% of all diseases are respiratory; ~33% children/infants suffer breathing difficulties and allergies
  • Healthcare: PMCH and NMCH primary government centers (both overburdened); only 20% of population gets healthcare facilities; significant infrastructure gaps despite being state capital
  • Seasonal Patterns: Strong winter peaks in respiratory infections; viral diseases surge with temperature changes; air pollution worsens symptoms Nov-Feb
  • Socioeconomic: Per capita income ₹66,828 (2023-24); richest district in Bihar contributing 27% of state GDP (~$30B); major administrative center but infrastructure challenges
